## 2. Addon Structure

### 2.1 TOC File

```
## Interface: 120000
## Title: MyAddon
## Notes: Short description
## Author: YourName
## Version: 1.0.0
## SavedVariables: MyAddonDB
## SavedVariablesPerCharacter: MyAddonCharDB
## Dependencies: SomeRequiredAddon
## OptionalDeps: Ace3
## Group: OneWoW

# Load order matters — libraries first, then core, then modules
libs\LibStub\LibStub.lua
libs\AceAddon-3.0\AceAddon-3.0.lua
libs\AceDB-3.0\AceDB-3.0.lua

Core.lua
Modules\SomeModule.lua
```

- TOC filename **must** match the addon folder name exactly.
- `## Interface:` accepts comma-separated values for multi-flavor support
  (e.g., `120000, 120005`). For Retail-only addons, use `120000` minimum.
- `## SavedVariables:` names become global tables persisted across sessions.
  They are loaded _before_ your addon code runs.
- Use `## Category:` for the addon list category (added in 11.1.0).
- Backslashes `\` are recommended for subdirectory paths in file listings.
- Lines starting with `#` (no second `#`) are comments.

**TOC format:** https://warcraft.wiki.gg/wiki/TOC_format

### 2.2 Addon Namespace

Every Lua file in an addon receives two implicit varargs:

```lua
local addonName, ns = ...
```

- `addonName` — string, the folder name of your addon.
- `ns` — a **private table** shared across all files in this addon. Use it
  instead of globals to pass data between files.

### 2.3 OneWoW Suite — OneWoW_GUI Dependency

**Every Lua file** that uses OneWoW_GUI must have this block **near the top**
(immediately after addon namespace setup and any minimal globals):

```lua
local OneWoW_GUI = LibStub("OneWoW_GUI-1.0", true)
if not OneWoW_GUI then return end
```

This applies to all files that call OneWoW_GUI — not just the main addon file.
Fail fast: if OneWoW_GUI is unavailable, the file exits immediately. No defensive
guards like `if OneWoW_GUI and OneWoW_GUI.SomeMethod then`. Call
`OneWoW_GUI.SomeMethod(...)` directly. When something fails (e.g. missing method),
it errors and gets fixed, not silently ignored.

### 2.3.2 OneWoW_GUI-First UI Policy (Mandatory)

All addon UI must be created via the OneWoW GUI addon whenever a matching
component/helper exists.

- **Do not build raw UI widgets first** (`CreateFrame`, `CreateFontString`,
  manual backdrops/buttons/scrollbars) when OneWoW_GUI already provides an
  equivalent helper/component.
- **Before adding or changing UI code**, check whether OneWoW_GUI already has a
  function for it and prefer that function.
- **Reduce custom UI code whenever possible**. Refactors should bias toward
  replacing custom UI construction with OneWoW_GUI calls to reduce duplicate
  code and improve consistency.
- If behavior requires changing a OneWoW_GUI function, **stop and discuss it
  first** before implementing local workarounds.
- If the needed UI function does not exist in OneWoW_GUI, **stop and discuss
  adding it** before introducing new custom UI patterns.
- If no OneWoW_GUI equivalent exists and work must proceed, clearly document
  why a temporary direct WoW UI call is required.

### 2.3.1 OneWoW_GUI Component API

OneWoW_GUI uses a consistent `CreateComponent(parent, options)` pattern: parent
first, all other parameters in `options`. Call OneWoW_GUI directly; do not add
Framework shims or wrappers. Examples:

```lua
OneWoW_GUI:CreateFitTextButton(parent, { text = L.SAVE, height = 24 })
OneWoW_GUI:CreateScrollFrame(parent, { name = "MyScroll" })
OneWoW_GUI:CreateSectionHeader(parent, { title = L.SECTION, yOffset = 0 })
```

**Button auto-sizing:** ALL buttons in every addon must auto-size to their text.
Different languages need different amounts of space; fixed-width buttons cause
truncation or overflow. Prefer `CreateFitTextButton` over `CreateButton` for
user-facing buttons. Only use fixed-width buttons when layout explicitly
requires it (e.g. a rigid grid).

### 2.4 OneWoW Suite — Theme Colors

Always use `OneWoW_GUI:GetThemeColor(key)` for theme colors. Do **not** access
raw theme data (e.g. `currentThemeData.ACCENT_PRIMARY` or
`unpack(currentThemeData.ACCENT_PRIMARY)`).

```lua
-- BAD: direct theme data access
if currentThemeData and currentThemeData.ACCENT_PRIMARY then
    themeColorPreview:SetColorTexture(unpack(currentThemeData.ACCENT_PRIMARY))
end

-- BAD: pass-through wrapper — adds extra function call overhead for no benefit
local GetThemeColor = function(key) return OneWoW_GUI:GetThemeColor(key) end

-- GOOD: use the API directly
themeColorPreview:SetColorTexture(OneWoW_GUI:GetThemeColor("ACCENT_PRIMARY"))
```

`GetThemeColor` returns `r, g, b, a` (suitable for `SetColorTexture`,
`SetBackdropColor`, `SetTextColor`, etc.). Centralizing theme access via the
API ensures consistency and correct behavior when themes change.

### 2.5 Constants & Localization

**No static strings in code.** All user-facing text (labels, tooltips, titles,
button text, error messages, etc.) must reference constants or translations.
Never hardcode display strings like `"Save"` or `"Cancel"` directly in UI code.

**Constants:** Every addon has `Addon/Core/Constants.lua`. Create it if it does
not exist. Constants are stored as `Addon.Constants.X` where `X` can be any
data type (tables, strings, numbers, etc.). Example:

```lua
-- MyAddon/Core/Constants.lua
Addon.Constants = Addon.Constants or {}
Addon.Constants.DEFAULT_SCALE = 1.0
Addon.Constants.KEY_SAVE = "SAVE"
```

**Translations:** All translations live in `Addon/Locales/` (e.g.
`MyAddon/Locales/enUS.lua`, `MyAddon/Locales/deDE.lua`). Reference them via
the addon's locale table (e.g. `L.SAVE`, `L.BUTTON_CANCEL`).

### 2.6 OneWoW Suite — Database API (Mandatory)

All OneWoW addons must use the shared `OneWoW_GUI.DB` API for SavedVariable
management. Do not hand-roll merge functions, ensure-if-nil blocks, or
per-addon default application logic. Full design rationale:
[OneWoW_GUI/Docs/DATABASE.md](OneWoW_GUI/Docs/DATABASE.md). For the API
surface, read `OneWoW_GUI/Database.lua` directly.

```lua
local OneWoW_GUI = LibStub("OneWoW_GUI-1.0", true)
if not OneWoW_GUI then return end
local DB = OneWoW_GUI.DB
```

**Key rules:**

- **`DB:Init`** initializes the database. Three modes: `single` (one
  SavedVariable root with `global`/`chars`), `split` (separate global +
  per-char SavedVariables), or `acedb` (wraps an existing AceDB handle).
  After `Init` returns, `db`, `db.global`, and every key in the defaults
  table are **guaranteed to exist**.
- **`DB:MergeMissing`** fills only `nil` keys — never overwrites user data.
  It replaces all custom `mergeSubTable` / `ApplyDefaults` / ensure-if-nil
  patterns.
- **`DB:RunMigrations`** runs versioned one-time data transformations.
  Migrations are structural changes (rename keys, move data). Defaults
  application is a normalizer handled by `Init` + `MergeMissing`, not a
  migration.
- **No defensive nil-chain guards after Init.** `DB:Init` and `MergeMissing`
  guarantee all defaulted keys exist. Do not write
  `Addon.db and Addon.db.global and Addon.db.global.X` chains or
  `Addon.db.global.X or defaultValue` when the default is already in the
  defaults table. These guards are dead code that obscures intent.

```lua
-- BAD: redundant guards — DB:Init guarantees these exist
local sortOrder = Addon.db and Addon.db.global and Addon.db.global.monitor
    and Addon.db.global.monitor.sortOrder or 2
if Addon.db and Addon.db.global then
    Addon.db.global.position = pos
end

-- GOOD: trust the DB API
local sortOrder = Addon.db.global.monitor.sortOrder
Addon.db.global.position = pos
```

- **`or {}` / `or default` is only appropriate for dynamic keys** not defined
  in the defaults table (e.g. `catMods[entryName] or {}`).
- **Shared settings** (`theme`, `language`, `minimap`) are managed by
  `OneWoW_GUI:GetSetting` / `OneWoW_GUI:SetSetting`. Addons must not store
  these locally.

