## 7. Coding Standards

### 7.1 Globals & Locals

- **Localize frequently-used globals** at the top of each file for performance
  and clarity:
  ```lua
  local pairs, ipairs, type = pairs, ipairs, type
  local CreateFrame = CreateFrame
  local C_Timer = C_Timer
  ```
- **Never pollute the global namespace.** Use the addon namespace (`ns`) or
  Ace3's addon object to share data between files.
- Name global frames sparingly with a unique prefix: `MyAddon_MainFrame`.

#### 7.1.5 WoW Table Globals

Prefer WoW's global table helpers over Lua's `table.*` functions:

- `tinsert` over `table.insert`
- `tremove` over `table.remove`
- `sort` over `table.sort`
- `wipe` over `table.wipe`

### 7.2 Performance

- Avoid allocations in OnUpdate, CLEU handlers, or any high-frequency path.
  Reuse tables with `wipe()`.
- Avoid string concatenation in loops; use `format()` or `table.concat()`.
- Cache API results that don't change mid-frame (e.g., `UnitName("player")`).
- Use `C_Timer.After` / `C_Timer.NewTicker` instead of OnUpdate when frame-
  perfect timing isn't required.
- For COMBAT_LOG_EVENT_UNFILTERED, always call `CombatLogGetCurrentEventInfo()`
  inside the handler — do NOT pass args via `...` (they don't exist for CLEU).

### 7.2.1 Compliance Baseline

- All code must comply with **WoW Retail Midnight 12.0.0.1** API behavior.
- Account for modern API changes (including **secret values** restrictions)
  when implementing or reviewing features.

### 7.3 Error Handling

```lua
local ok, err = pcall(riskyFunction, arg1, arg2)
if not ok then
    -- handle error, don't silently swallow it
    print("MyAddon error:", err)
end
```

### 7.4 SavedVariables

- **OneWoW addons:** Use `OneWoW_GUI.DB:Init` (see section 2.6). Do not use
  raw SavedVariable init or AceDB directly for new OneWoW addons.
- Initialize defaults on `ADDON_LOADED` or in Ace3's `OnInitialize`.
- Always validate / migrate saved data — the user might have data from an
  older version. In OneWoW addons, use `DB:RunMigrations` for this.
- Use AceDB when possible for non-OneWoW addons; it handles profile
  management and defaults.

### 7.5 Tooltip System (Modern — 10.0.2+)

The tooltip system was **completely rewritten** in Dragonflight (10.0.2).
The old `OnTooltipSetItem`/`OnTooltipSetSpell` script handlers are **removed**.
GameTooltip no longer exposes native methods for retrieving or populating
tooltip contents directly. There are now three key patterns:

#### 7.5.1 Displaying Simple Custom Tooltips

For basic addon-owned tooltips (hover info on your own frames), the
`SetOwner` / `SetText` / `AddLine` / `Show` pattern still works:

```lua
frame:SetScript("OnEnter", function(self)
    GameTooltip:SetOwner(self, "ANCHOR_RIGHT")
    GameTooltip:SetText("Title", 1, 1, 1)             -- white title
    GameTooltip:AddLine("Description text", nil, nil, nil, true) -- wrap
    GameTooltip:AddDoubleLine("Left", "Right", 1,1,1, 0.5,0.5,0.5)
    GameTooltip:Show()
end)
frame:SetScript("OnLeave", GameTooltip_Hide)
```

#### 7.5.2 Hooking Into Existing Tooltips (TooltipDataProcessor)

To add lines or modify tooltips for items, spells, units, etc., use
`TooltipDataProcessor.AddTooltipPostCall`. This **replaces** the old
`GameTooltip:HookScript("OnTooltipSetItem", ...)` pattern.

```lua
-- Add extra info to item tooltips
TooltipDataProcessor.AddTooltipPostCall(Enum.TooltipDataType.Item,
    function(tooltip, data)
        if tooltip == GameTooltip then
            tooltip:AddLine("My custom line", 0.5, 1, 0.5)
        end
    end
)

-- For spell tooltips, use Enum.TooltipDataType.Spell
-- For unit tooltips, use Enum.TooltipDataType.Unit
-- For ALL tooltip types, use TooltipDataProcessor.AllTypes (or "ALL")
```

There are also `AddTooltipPreCall`, `AddLinePreCall`, and `AddLinePostCall`
variants for more granular control.

**Important:** Callbacks registered with TooltipDataProcessor are global —
they fire for ALL tooltip frames inheriting `GameTooltipTemplate`. Always
check `tooltip == GameTooltip` (or your specific tooltip) if you only want
to modify a particular tooltip instance.

#### 7.5.3 Scanning / Extracting Tooltip Data (C_TooltipInfo)

To programmatically read tooltip information **without displaying a tooltip**
(replaces the old hidden-tooltip scanning technique), use `C_TooltipInfo`:

```lua
-- Get structured tooltip data for an item
local tooltipData = C_TooltipInfo.GetItemByID(itemID)
if tooltipData then
    TooltipUtil.SurfaceArgs(tooltipData)    -- REQUIRED: populates fields
    for _, line in ipairs(tooltipData.lines) do
        TooltipUtil.SurfaceArgs(line)       -- REQUIRED per line
        -- line.leftText, line.rightText, line.type, etc. now accessible
        print(line.leftText)
    end
end

-- Other C_TooltipInfo functions:
-- C_TooltipInfo.GetUnit(unitToken)
-- C_TooltipInfo.GetSpellByID(spellID)
-- C_TooltipInfo.GetHyperlink(hyperlink)
-- C_TooltipInfo.GetUnitAura(unit, index, filter)
-- C_TooltipInfo.GetUnitBuffByAuraInstanceID(unit, auraInstanceID)
-- C_TooltipInfo.GetEquipmentSet(name)
-- C_TooltipInfo.GetItemByItemLink(itemLink)
-- ... and many more (see warcraft.wiki.gg/wiki/Category:API_systems/TooltipInfo)
```

**Critical:** You MUST call `TooltipUtil.SurfaceArgs()` on the returned
`tooltipData` and on each `line` entry before accessing fields like
`leftText`, `type`, `guid`, etc. Without this call, those fields are nil.

#### 7.5.4 Custom Tooltip Frames

If creating your own GameTooltip-type frame, it **must** inherit
`GameTooltipTemplate` (which includes `GameTooltipDataMixin` for automatic
handling of `TOOLTIP_DATA_UPDATE` events):

```lua
local myTooltip = CreateFrame("GameTooltip", "MyAddonTooltip", UIParent,
    "GameTooltipTemplate")
```

#### 7.5.5 Key Enum.TooltipDataType Values

`Item`, `Spell`, `Unit`, `UnitAura`, `Currency`, `Mount`, `Macro`,
`Achievement`, `Quest`, `QuestPartyProgress`, `BattlePet`, `Toy`,
`Hyperlink`, `MinimapPing`, `EquipmentSet`.

### 7.6 Menus (Modern)

The old `UIDropDownMenu` system is deprecated. Use `MenuUtil` in 12.0+:

```lua
MenuUtil.CreateContextMenu(ownerFrame, function(ownerRegion, rootDescription)
    rootDescription:CreateTitle("My Menu")
    rootDescription:CreateButton("Option 1", function() ... end)
    rootDescription:CreateCheckbox("Toggle", isChecked, function() ... end)
end)
```

### 7.7 Closures & Frame Scripts

Pitfalls when writing frame scripts and event handlers in WoW addons.

**Closure variable order:** Variables captured by closures (e.g. `OnClick` handlers) must be **declared and initialized before** the handler is defined. If declared after, the closure can reference `nil` at runtime.

```lua
-- BAD: customRefreshCallbacks is nil when OnClick runs
toggleBtn:SetScript("OnClick", function()
    for _, fn in ipairs(customRefreshCallbacks) do fn() end  -- error: nil
end)
local customRefreshCallbacks = {}

-- GOOD: declare and init first
local customRefreshCallbacks = {}
local function registerRefresh(fn) tinsert(customRefreshCallbacks, fn) end
toggleBtn:SetScript("OnClick", function()
    for _, fn in ipairs(customRefreshCallbacks) do fn() end
end)
```

**Stale upvalue sync:** When a callback updates state that closures depend on, reassign the upvalue in that callback so the closure sees the new value.

```lua
local isEnabled = false
local function refresh(enabled, ...)
    isEnabled = enabled  -- keep closure's upvalue in sync
    for _, btn in ipairs(toggleBtnSets) do
        btn:EnableMouse(enabled)
        -- ...
    end
end
```

**Button event order:** For Button widgets: OnMouseDown → OnMouseUp → PreClick → OnClick → PostClick. OnMouseUp runs **before** OnClick.

**Radio-style / active-state buttons:** Buttons created with `CreateButton` (or similar) use default OnEnter/OnLeave handlers that revert to BTN_NORMAL when the mouse leaves. For radio-style buttons where one option stays visually "active" after selection, that OnLeave overwrites your custom active styling.

**Fix:** Use `HookScript("OnLeave", UpdateStyling)` instead of `SetScript`. The hook runs after the default handler, so your refresh reapplies the correct styling based on the active state.

**SetScript vs HookScript:**

- `SetScript` — replaces the handler.
- `HookScript` — appends to the existing handler. Use when layering behavior on top of Blizzard or other addon handlers.

**Modular UI refresh:** When a parent action (e.g. main Enable/Disable) must refresh child UI in custom modules, use a `registerRefresh` pattern so modules can register callbacks that the parent invokes.

```lua
local customRefreshCallbacks = {}
local function registerRefresh(fn) tinsert(customRefreshCallbacks, fn) end
-- Pass registerRefresh to CreateCustomDetail; modules call registerRefresh(UpdateRow)
-- Parent's toggle handler: for _, fn in ipairs(customRefreshCallbacks) do fn() end
```

