## 9. Common Mistakes to Avoid

1. **Using removed/deprecated APIs.** If you learned WoW addon dev before
   Dragonflight, many APIs you knew have moved to `C_*` namespaces or been
   removed entirely. Always check the wiki.
2. **Modifying secure frames in combat.** This will silently fail or throw
   taint errors. Gate all secure frame modifications behind
   `not InCombatLockdown()`.
3. **Hardcoding spell/item IDs without fallbacks.** IDs can change between
   patches. Prefer name-based lookups with ID as cache keys, and always
   nil-check returns.
4. **Forgetting that CLEU doesn't pass event args via `...`.** You MUST call
   `CombatLogGetCurrentEventInfo()` inside the handler.
5. **Creating frames in a loop without pooling.** Use `CreateFramePool` or
   manually pool/recycle frames.
6. **Using `UIDropDownMenu` in new code.** It's deprecated; use `MenuUtil`.
7. **Using `OnTooltipSetItem` / `OnTooltipSetSpell` hooks.** These script
   handlers were removed in 10.0.2. Use `TooltipDataProcessor.AddTooltipPostCall`
   with `Enum.TooltipDataType.*` instead. Also don't create hidden
   `GameTooltip` frames for scanning — use `C_TooltipInfo` + `TooltipUtil.SurfaceArgs`.
8. **Not testing inside instances.** Secret value restrictions often only
   apply in instanced content. Your addon may work in the open world and
   break in dungeons/raids.
9. **Writing to global table keys carelessly.** Every addon shares the same
   global environment. A stray `count = 0` at file scope clobbers (and
   taints) any other addon's `count` global.
10. **Assuming SavedVariables exist on first load.** They're `nil` until the
    player has logged out at least once with your addon enabled.
11. **Calling API functions too early.** Many APIs return nil before
    `PLAYER_LOGIN`. Don't query unit info or map data at file load time.
12. **Closure/upvalue pitfalls in frame scripts.** Event handlers capture
    variables by reference. Declare and initialize variables used by
    closures _before_ defining the handler. When a callback updates state
    that closures depend on, reassign the upvalue in that callback (e.g.
    `isEnabled = enabled`). See section 7.7.
13. **Fixed-width buttons.** Buttons must auto-size to text for localization.
    Use `CreateFitTextButton` (or equivalent) — fixed widths cause truncation
    in other languages.
14. **Static strings in UI code.** Never hardcode user-facing strings. Use
    `Addon.Constants` (in `Core/Constants.lua`) or locale tables in
    `Addon/Locales/` (e.g. `L.SAVE`). See section 2.5.
15. **Fullscreen overlay above host for popup dismiss.** A `UIParent`-parented
    overlay above the host window catches clicks but **consumes** them —
    forcing a second click to activate the control underneath. Use the
    OnUpdate hybrid pattern instead (section 4.7): OnUpdate detects
    `IsMouseButtonDown` transitions while `IsMouseOver()` is false. Input
    fires before OnUpdate in the same frame, so both the control action and
    the dismiss happen on a single click.
16. **Reusing FontStrings across different FontObjects.** `SetFontObject()`
    does not clear local overrides from explicit setter calls
    (`SetJustifyH`, `SetTextColor`, `SetFont`, etc.). Properties from a
    previous font "stick" to subsequent selections. Recreate the FontString
    or read values from the Font object directly. See section 4.8.
17. **Defensive nil-chain guards on DB-initialized keys.** After
    `DB:Init` + `MergeMissing`, all defaulted keys are guaranteed to exist.
    Writing `Addon.db and Addon.db.global and Addon.db.global.X` or
    `Addon.db.global.X or defaultValue` (when the default is in the
    defaults table) is dead code that hides intent. Trust the DB API.
    See section 2.6.

